# Fixture IRI-001: remove-dots above-root path
#
# RFC 3986 §5.2.4 "remove_dot_segments" must not allow `..` steps to
# escape the root. All four references below use the same base; their
# resolved IRIs are specified in comments.
#
# Hypothesis: An implementation that naively iterates `..` removals
# without a "cannot go above root" guard will produce `http://d` for
# the last triple (treating the root `/` as removable) instead of the
# required `http://example/d`.  RFC 3986 §5.2.4 step 2C requires that
# a leading `/../` be treated as `/`.
#
# Spec: RFC 3986 §5.2.4 (remove_dot_segments algorithm)
#       IETF Errata 4005 (path-segment boundary during remove_dot_segments)

@base <http://example/a/b/c> .
@prefix p: <http://example.org/pred/> .

# 1-level up: http://example/a/d
<../d>     p:name "one-level-up" .

# 2-levels up: http://example/d
<../../d>  p:name "two-levels-up" .

# 3-levels up (at root): http://example/
<../../..>  p:name "three-levels-up-at-root" .

# 4-levels up (CANNOT go above root): must be http://example/d, not http://d
<../../../d>  p:name "above-root-clamped" .
